üìù Important Aspects & Key Concepts
Networking models & terms: Knowing OSI vs TCP/IP layers, what each layer does, typical protocols; this helps you map vulnerabilities and controls to layers.
Protocol/port identification: E.g., HTTP ‚Üí port 80 (insecure) vs HTTPS ‚Üí port 443 (secure). Recognizing legacy/insecure services (Telnet 23, FTP 21) versus modern secure ones (SSH, SFTP).
HACKLIDO
Threats and attacks: Understanding how threats exploit network protocols and services, how attackers move laterally, and how design choices (like segmentation) matter.
Security infrastructure & design:
On-premises: making sure data centre physical/environmental factors are known (power, HVAC etc).
Cloud: Understanding service models and deployment models, what implications they have for network security.
Design concepts: VLANs, DMZ, VPN, micro-segmentation, zero trust, defense in depth. These aren‚Äôt just buzzwords‚Äîthey reflect how you structure a network to resist or limit attacks.
Secure configuration and architecture as baseline: It‚Äôs not enough to know the threats; you must be able to think about how networks should be configured, segmented, controlled.
Terminology mastery: Many exam questions will test your ability to identify correct terminology or match terms to concepts. The learning objectives stress recognizing and using the correct terms. 
CSDN Blog
+1
Holistic view: Even though this is a ‚Äúnetwork‚Äù chapter, the goal is to see how networking fits into cybersecurity as a broader domain‚Äînot just bits and ports, but context, risk, architecture.
